&gt; &gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; &quot;Alex&quot; == Alex Jacobson &lt;alex@...&gt; writes:
&gt;
&gt;     Alex&gt; I think it is goofy that ReST means that I can have
&gt;     Alex&gt; absolutely no idea what the effect of PUT or POST actually
&gt;     Alex&gt; is without an extended out of band conversation with the web
&gt;     Alex&gt; server operator.
&gt;
&gt; That&#39;s true for every routine and function you call in this world. The
&gt; solution to this (not widely used yet, too many people seem to love C)
&gt; is the notion of pre- and postcondition:
&gt;
&gt; 1. If the client fullfills its part of the obligation, i.e. meeting
&gt;    all the conditions stated in the precondition,
&gt;
&gt; 2. then the server fullfills its part of the obligation, i.e. meeting
&gt;    all the conditions stated in the postcondition.
&gt;
&gt; Everything beyond that is of no concern to the client.
&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Explicit pre- and postconditions are missing from REST, but that it is
&gt; all you need. If the precondition states that you can PUT, you can. If
&gt; the postcondition states that the result of the PUT is that a GET
&gt; returns the putted resource, than that&#39;s all there is.
&gt;
&gt; If you seek an understanding of how different resouces work together
&gt; and how to accomplish certain tasks (booking a meeting with different
&gt; participans for example), that has and will always be part of the
&gt; documentation. That&#39;s just part of the architecture. UI don&#39;t see any
&gt; metamodel solving that problem.
